                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-155524 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-chicago-ill tag-fires-and-firefighters tag-real-estate-and-housing-residential des-fires-and-firefighters des-real-estate-and-housing-residential geo-chicago-ill news_keywords-chicago-2 news_keywords-fires-2 news_keywords-real-estate-and-housing"
                                id="post-155524">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">What Would You Grab in a Fire?</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Megan Stielstra			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-01-14T23:51:02+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">January 14, 2015 6:51 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">January 14, 2015 6:51 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">CHICAGO &#x2014; I was getting ready for bed when I heard sirens. No big deal in the city, right? We hear them all the time. I brushed my teeth &#x2014; they got louder. Tossed my pants on the bathroom floor &#x2014;
                                        louder, closer, and when I went into the living room I saw red lights slicing through the blinds. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;What the &#x2014;?&#x201D; said my husband, getting up from the couch, and that&#x2019;s when we heard pounding on the door. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We rent the second floor of a three-flat apartment building in Chicago. The layout is typical: living room and bedroom in the front; dining room and bathroom in the middle; kitchen and a second bedroom in the back.
                                        We moved in a year ago, after bailing on the condo we&#x2019;d bought just before the market crashed. Everything happened so fast: One day we had a home and then &#x2014; snap your fingers &#x2014; it was worthless.
                                        <span id="more-155524"></span></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Underwater,&#x201D; they call it, which is a poetic way of saying that you&#x2019;re drowning. We couldn&#x2019;t sell. We&#x2019;d just had a baby. I&#x2019;d just gotten sick. My husband took a second job.
                                        I got better and took a third, then a fourth, 60-hour weeks of hustling, passing our son between us. It was a wild whiplash between gratitude &#x2014; we had the jobs, the home, each other &#x2014; and exhaustion.
                                        One day I woke up and five years had passed. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At some point, you have ask yourself how you want to live. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One morning, I typed &#x201C;beach&#x201D; into Craigslist and an apartment came up along the lakefront. It had a working fireplace. The rent was half our monthly mortgage. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My husband and I talked about what would happen to our credit, to our future. And a week later, I was on our new front porch, listening to Lake Michigan wave against the sand. My 5-year-old son sat on my lap. I felt
                                        him breathing: Slow. Easy. Calm. &#x201C;It&#x2019;s nice to be home,&#x201D; he said. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was that first deep drink of air after coming up from underwater.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So imagine how it felt when my upstairs neighbor pounded on our door and told us the building was on fire. </p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/15/opinion/0115PRIVATELIVES/0115PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/15/opinion/0115PRIVATELIVES/0115PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/15/opinion/0115PRIVATELIVES/0115PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000003450393" width="480" height="585" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="585">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sam Alden</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He stood in the hall, red lights strobing, sirens screaming, not noticing that my husband and I were in our underwear. &#x201C;We had a fire in the fireplace,&#x201D; he told us. &#x201C;It died out like always, we
                                        went to bed, were about to fall asleep but &#x2014; you know that feeling when you forgot to check the locks?&#x201D; Thankfully he got up, because when he walked into his living room, the wall behind his fireplace
                                        burst into flames.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He ran downstairs to warn our first-floor neighbors, leaving our front door open. I could smell smoke. The sirens had multiplied &#x2014; three fire trucks outside, maybe four. I turned toward the front of the apartment:
                                        our books and art and photos lit red and flashing; then I turned to the back, where my now 6-year-old son was fast asleep in his bedroom off the kitchen. There were 20 steps between him and me. Twenty steps and
                                        we&#x2019;d be out the back door, down the back stairs, into the car and out of there.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I&#x2019;ll get him,&#x201D; I shouted to my husband.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Great,&#x201D; he said, already moving. &#x201C;I&#x2019;ll grab some stuff and meet you in the car.&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I remember thinking, stuff? What stuff? How do you decide, the clock ticking? Years earlier, I&#x2019;d made a list of the things I&#x2019;d grab in a fire: Books. Photos. Art. Back then, objects were sacred; not people.
                                        Back then, I hadn&#x2019;t experienced loss. The question isn&#x2019;t, What would you grab in a fire? It&#x2019;s, What has meaning in our lives? </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the way to my son&#x2019;s room, I stopped to put on pants; I put a toothbrush in one pocket and moisturizer in the other. Then I ran into the bedroom and grabbed the hunting knife from my bedside table, the one
                                        my dad had given me when I started living alone, and slid it under my waistband. How long did that take? &#x2014; two minutes? &#x2014; but during that time my husband, still in his underpants, ran to the back of
                                        the house carrying our laptops, hard drive and iPads. It&#x2019;s safe to say that he values technology. It&#x2019;s expensive, of course, but it&#x2019;s more than that: In those laptops is the website he built,
                                        the one that supports our family. It also holds the novel I&#x2019;m working on. It didn&#x2019;t occur to me to grab my novel. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What occurred to me was pants. Toiletries. Knife. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kid. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He sleeps through everything. The condo we&#x2019;d left behind was across the street from the Aragon Ballroom, a rock club on Chicago&#x2019;s North Side. While my husband and I tried to pay bills, to make it to the
                                        end of the month, to peel me out of the postpartum depression that almost leveled us, our perfect little boy would fall asleep to that night&#x2019;s headliner: Marilyn Manson, the Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Megadeth. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I slung him, still sleeping, over my shoulder, ran down the back stairs, and into the snow-covered alley. I wore pants, but no shoes. My feet were so cold they were on fire. I slid into the front seat with him on my
                                        lap, next to my husband who was already behind the wheel. The heat was blasting. The dog cowered on the floor. In front of us, our building loomed three stories high, enormous and eerie and backlit flashing red.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It happened so fast: One day we had a home and then &#x2014; snap your fingers.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Where should we go?&#x201D; my husband asked. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I listed names, and with each remembered how profoundly lucky we were. Our friends would take us in. Our kid wouldn&#x2019;t remember a thing. Our upstairs neighbor had gotten up to check his locks. Our downstairs neighbor,
                                        we&#x2019;d later learn, was a veteran of the Chicago Fire Department; he&#x2019;d run upstairs in his pajamas and attacked the third floor with a crowbar, ripping clear a pathway for the hoses and extinguishers
                                        and chemicals that wiped the flames away before they spread. This was one of a thousand nights that could&#x2019;ve gone one way, but it went another.<br> An hour later, we&#x2019;d get the call that it was safe,
                                        but just then we drove down the alley, leaving yet another home behind. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I wrapped my body around my son&#x2019;s, feeling him breathe: Slow. Easy. Calm.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That first, deep drink of air.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.meganstielstra.com/" title="Megan Stielstra">Megan Stielstra</a> is the author of the essay collection &#x201C;Once I Was Cool.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 01/18/2015, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">9</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">National</span> edition with
                                                the headline: What Would You Grab in a Fire?.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
                                </div>
